  scenario="It is 4pm on a Sunday. A homeowner in Wantage is looking at her back garden after a windy night — the fence panel between her garden and the footpath behind the house has blown clean off, the concrete gravel board is cracked, and anyone walking on the path can see straight into her garden. She opens Facebook, searches 'fencing Wantage,' and finds your page. Your most recent post shows a completed close board fence — smart, professional, with concrete posts and gravel boards. She sends a Messenger message: 'Hi, we have lost a panel at the back where we adjoin the footpath. The gravel board is cracked too. We need it replaced quickly — my daughter's bedroom window looks straight onto the gap. Can you come this week?' Without AI Facebook Messenger, you see the message Monday afternoon. She has already had a fencing contractor recommended by a friend on Facebook and booked a Tuesday visit. With AI Messenger, the reply comes back in seconds: 'Sorry to hear about the panel — that must be concerning with the footpath access. Could you send a photo of the damage and share your postcode? One of our team will call you first thing tomorrow to arrange a visit.' She sends a photo showing the gap, the cracked gravel board, and the exposed footpath. Monday morning you open a lead with the photo, the urgency (child safety and footpath access), and the postcode. You call at 8am, visit at lunchtime with a replacement panel, post, and gravel board on the van, and have the fence repaired by 3pm."
